{{for|Frederick Nodder, executed in 1937|Murder conviction without a body}}
[[Image:Bruguiera gymnorrhiza00.jpg|thumb|<center>''[[Bruguiera gymnorhiza]]''<br>by<br>Frederick Polydore Nodder]]
'''Frederick Polydore Nodder''' ([[floruit|fl.]] 1770 – c. 1800) was an [[England|English]] [[plant|flora]] and [[animal|fauna]] [[illustrator]], a copperplate engraver and a miniature painter.

Nodder illustrated [[George Shaw]]'s periodical ''The Naturalist's Miscellany''. He also helped [[Joseph Banks]] prepare the ''[[Banks' Florilegium]]'' and converted most of [[Sydney Parkinson]]'s [[Australia]]n plant drawings from the [[HMS Endeavour|HMS ''Endeavour'']] expedition into paintings and helped engrave them for publication. There are Nodder drawings and paintings of Australian birds and butterflies in the Natural History Division of the [[National Museum of Ireland]].<ref>http://www.anbg.gov.au/biography/nodder-frederick.html</ref>
{{Commons category|Frederick Polydore Nodder}}

